                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d727">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">338.1121 Zrike Bros. and Johnson/75:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Armour</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port-au-Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-07-26T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >July 26, 1933—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>81. Department’s telegram No. 51, July 25, 2 p.m. The Haitian Government today
                    accepted $10,400 as full restitution by Johnson for bribes received from Zrike
                    Brothers and released him on his own cognizance. It is understood that both
                    Johnson and Zrike Brothers are still liable to prosecution on criminal charges.
                    It is not known whether the Government intends to institute such
                    prosecution.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Armour</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
